00:53.160 --> 00:58.600
Although he appeared in print for the first time in 1969 with a short story in the Science Fiction Magazine,

01:03.340 --> 01:10.720
the novel was serialized in astounding science fiction starting in 1972, then released as a book in 1974.

01:11.800 --> 01:17.300
The Forever War is similar to Robert Heinlein's book Starship Troopers, in that both have intergalactic war,

01:17.540 --> 01:20.420
powered body armor, and highly advanced weapons as common elements.

01:21.060 --> 01:24.180
Differences between the books show up in the way the authors treat war.

01:24.720 --> 01:28.460
Heinlein's conflict was sort of a John Wayne style battle with the bad guys,

01:28.940 --> 01:33.600
whereas Haldeman's dealt with the emotions and reactions of his characters to the war they fought.

01:34.000 --> 01:35.920
We asked Haldeman if the resemblance was intentional.

01:37.060 --> 01:40.500
Well, there was no intention on my part.

01:41.120 --> 01:49.440
In fact, I didn't realize until I was about 70 or 80 pages into the book that many of the details were similar to Starship Troopers.

01:49.820 --> 01:52.260
Somebody else pointed that out when he read the manuscript.

01:53.360 --> 01:56.640
I wasn't doing an answer to Heinlein's book.

01:56.720 --> 02:03.020
I thought Heinlein's book was admirable in many ways, even though we have diametrically opposed philosophies.

02:05.840 --> 02:13.920
But if there's any relation to any book, it is to my own first novel, War Year,

02:14.840 --> 02:24.840
because it's an expansion into a science fiction universe of the notions that I was trying to express in mainstream novel.

02:43.660 --> 02:49.800
Haldeman has a background in physics and astronomy and told us about how he uses his hard science background in his work.

02:50.800 --> 02:55.540
Well, I try to use it to make the worlds that are in the event more believable,

02:56.420 --> 03:01.660
at least to me, since I do have a background in science and engineering.

03:01.940 --> 03:09.000
I think, well, the writer has to at least suspend his own disbelief while he's making up these stories.

03:09.340 --> 03:13.600
It's easier for me to do it if it's on a fairly solid scientific foundation,

03:14.560 --> 03:22.240
even though my science is rather old fashioned and probably rather sloppy by a real scientist's standards.

03:22.240 --> 03:27.120
It's still enough to convince me, so it's fulfilled its function.

03:34.300 --> 03:39.360
In the Forever War, the soldiers experience time dilation when they travel to and from the war zone.

03:39.780 --> 03:44.740
That means that due to the tremendous velocity of their spaceships, dozens of years have passed on Earth,

03:45.000 --> 03:47.980
while only a few months have passed for the soldiers on the spaceships.

03:47.980 --> 03:52.720
Haldeman told us how he used hard science to evoke some of the feeling the soldiers have.

03:53.780 --> 04:00.940
It goes deeper than just description, the time dilation in the Forever War,

04:01.380 --> 04:06.200
though it's scientifically accurate, its main function is metaphorical,

04:07.040 --> 04:16.000
and that is to demonstrate how the soldiers who fight a war become isolated from the culture that they're supposed to be protecting.

04:16.860 --> 04:23.440
He was using a science-fictional device to exaggerate something that happened to every soldier.

04:25.180 --> 04:31.040
I remember when I came back from Vietnam, I was suddenly plunged into what was an alien culture,

04:31.220 --> 04:33.940
even though I'd only been a soldier for two years.

04:35.280 --> 04:41.900
A lot of things had changed, and it's not a great thing to come back.

04:41.900 --> 04:44.840
There were no victory parades, and that sort of thing.

04:57.480 --> 05:00.600
Join us next time when we continue our interview with Joe Haldeman.

