06:46.160 --> 06:51.520
It was mentioned in the previous program that Haldeman served in Vietnam and uses that experience in some of his stories.

06:52.200 --> 06:56.740
For instance, in one of his stories, he tells of a soldier who is severely hurt by a laser mine.

06:56.740 --> 06:59.920
We asked Haldeman if that was drawn from his own experiences.

07:37.920 --> 07:42.680
We wondered if he was exercising demons by writing about that experience.

07:57.140 --> 08:00.880
We asked if being in Vietnam had any other effects on his writing.

08:51.080 --> 08:55.160
Haldeman has written two novels and edited one anthology, all dealing with war.

08:55.500 --> 08:56.720
But by no means should you consider the fact that Haldeman is a writer.

08:58.940 --> 09:03.500
That's right, he writes about what happens to people who are placed in that type of violent situation.

09:04.340 --> 09:09.600
He seems to be exploring what makes his characters tick more than the situations surrounding the characters.

09:10.060 --> 09:14.680
One of the themes in his work is man or mankind being changed when facing conflict.

09:14.900 --> 09:16.460
We asked Haldeman to respond to that.

09:17.380 --> 09:23.920
I think it's obvious that confronting death on a daily basis changes people.

09:24.580 --> 09:30.320
Sometimes radically for the worse, and that people who are totally dehumanized by war.

09:32.480 --> 09:36.760
But speaking racially, I don't think you could make such a broad statement.

09:37.860 --> 09:45.760
What's behind some of the things I'm writing is the hope that human nature eventually may improve to the point where we won't have wars.

09:45.760 --> 09:50.300
We find other ways to settle our differences.

09:52.220 --> 09:58.860
In his novel All My Sins Remembered, the main character is red-taped and shuffled into doing something that he is diametrically opposed to.

09:59.360 --> 10:02.080
When he rebels against the situation, he is terminated.

10:03.840 --> 10:09.500
The story is about a bureaucracy that totally takes over a man's identity.

10:09.500 --> 10:13.140
And he doesn't really exist except as a tool for that bureaucracy.

10:13.840 --> 10:17.060
When he becomes an efficient tool, he's scrapped.

10:18.380 --> 10:23.080
The main character ends up being a spy for the government and carrying out covert operations for them.

10:24.820 --> 10:33.640
And he goes more or less against his will, that is to say, through very advanced techniques of conditioning.

10:33.980 --> 10:36.200
He's turned into a thoroughly different person.

10:36.200 --> 10:39.820
He was a Buddhist, a pacifist when he started out.

10:40.900 --> 10:43.560
He did not get the job he signed up for.

10:43.740 --> 10:47.180
They twisted him around into being a killing machine.

10:48.820 --> 10:52.520
If all this makes Haldeman sound like a pessimist, well, he's not that either.

10:52.960 --> 10:55.820
Join us next time when we find out more about Joe Haldeman.

