12:36.040 --> 12:42.780
So far in our conversation with Haldeman, we've discussed how he used his experiences in Vietnam in his writing and some of his early works.

12:43.320 --> 12:46.220
Now we're going to look at his writing style and two particular stories.

12:46.220 --> 12:51.080
A short story to Howard Hughes' A Modest Proposal and a novel, Mindbridge.

12:51.740 --> 12:57.900
Haldeman tells these stories by using narratives by the main characters in the stories, reports by them and others,

12:58.300 --> 13:03.480
portions of books written long after the time set in the story, and other non-standard writing techniques.

13:04.100 --> 13:08.880
We asked him if he got the ideas for this type of style when he was attending the Iowa Writers Conference.

13:10.000 --> 13:14.240
Oh, not really. The connection is with John Doe's process. Thanks, David.

13:15.700 --> 13:25.360
I read the U.S. H. Reliative some years before at Mindbridge and really was impressed by the way it worked and thought it worked really well in science fiction.

13:26.240 --> 13:32.120
So I tried it out in a rather long short story, to Howard Hughes' A Modest Proposal.

13:33.220 --> 13:37.740
And it looked like it would work, so I went ahead and applied it to Mindbridge.

13:39.340 --> 13:44.360
I did do most of that book while I was studying at Iowa, and that's why I did a case.

13:46.060 --> 13:50.240
The authors at the Iowa Writers Conference were, for the most part, not science fiction writers.

13:50.740 --> 13:53.740
We asked Haldeman about their reaction to his being a science fiction author.

13:54.940 --> 14:01.000
Well, they were a little apprehensive about it. See, they didn't know I was a science fiction writer when I joined the workshop.

14:01.800 --> 14:06.300
So I joined on the basis of my first novel, which was not science fiction.

14:07.580 --> 14:13.180
And some of them were outwardly hostile towards science fiction, such as Stanley Elkham.

14:14.160 --> 14:18.740
Others were anywhere between apprehensive and slightly sympathetic.

14:19.540 --> 14:25.260
Stephen Becker, one of them, had actually had a few pieces in the magazine, Fantasy and Science Fiction.

14:25.260 --> 14:38.300
In general, though, they thinly disguised the attitude that this stuff was just commercial fiction, and therefore beneath contempt.

14:39.960 --> 14:44.420
That's an attitude I've never understood. Some of the world's finest literature is science fiction.

14:45.000 --> 14:47.580
We asked Haldeman what he thought about that type of attitude.

14:48.640 --> 14:52.540
But the field is judged by its worst, not by its best.

14:53.600 --> 15:00.840
And people like that think of science fiction, they think in terms of great D-movies and Lousy television.

15:02.200 --> 15:05.260
They've never read much of the best of the field.

15:11.680 --> 15:19.640
Using science fiction is possible to consider various aspects of mankind's future, and science fiction is the only literary form to speculate about the future.

15:20.200 --> 15:23.760
We asked Haldeman if he thought that mankind might be radically different in the future.

15:25.040 --> 15:29.600
I think it's quite possible, even say within the span of a century,

15:29.600 --> 15:43.760
so many of the things that determine human nature are things that can be mitigated by technology, such as the problem of dying so soon.

15:44.680 --> 15:54.940
That is, it's possible that in a couple of generations, being to live a century, two centuries, maybe a thousand years, maybe as long as you care to,

15:54.940 --> 16:01.180
that will radically change human nature because it will take the pressure off of individuals.

16:04.300 --> 16:17.060
The other or other less so sanguine notions is possible that the sciences of communication will grow into a kind of sophisticated mind control.

16:18.460 --> 16:25.120
It will be difficult for the individual to know exactly what is his idea and what has been induced by his own society.

16:26.400 --> 16:34.320
Sort of a sophisticated life-long brainwashing doesn't seem too unlikely, and you can argue that it's happening now.

